ξ 8. Tm lex Iulia maiestatis was passed by Julius Caesar, Cic. Philipp. 1. 9. Previously the law ol treason had tested partly on usage (Livy 1. 26), partly on the Twelve Tables (Dig. 48. 4. 3. pn), and a lex Comelia (Cic. in Pis. 21, pro Cluent. 35). The intention to commit the offence was punished no less than its execution (moliti sunt): ‘qui cogitaverit ....eadem enim severitate voluntatem sceleris, qua eflectum, puniri iura voluerunt’ cod. 9 8. 5. Perhaps the same rule was observed in all crimes, ‘in maleficiis voluntas spectatur, non exitus' Dig. ad leg. Corn. de sicariis 488. 44 The lex lulia had substituted a perpetual aquae et ignis interdictio sor the older punishment os death, Paul. sent. rec. 5. 29. 1 ; but the latter was re·established as early as Tiberius, Tac. Aun. 6. 18, Suetonius, Tiberius 58 sq.

Memoriae damnatio (lor which cl. Bk. iii. 1. 5 supr.) was an exception from the general rule ‘extinguitur crimen mortalitate’ Dig. 48. 4. 11 ; its effect was bonorum publicatio or confiscation, involving rescission ol the criminal’s will and donationes inter vimm et uxorem. A constitution oi M. Aurelius (Cod. 9. 8. 8) introduced the practice of finding persons guilty of treason aster their decease, which was unknown in the age of Tiberius, Tac. Ann. 6. 29.
